Definition 5.3. $\mathbf{C}$ is (right) coherent if $\mathsf{mod}(\mathbf{C})$ is an abelian category.
Definition 4.1. Let $\mathbf{B}\subseteq\mathsf{C}_{\mathrm{dg}}(\mathbf{A})$ be a full dg-subcategory. We define the dg-category $\operatorname{MC}(\mathbf{B})$ of Maurer-Cartan objects of $\mathbf{B}$ as follows: • Objects of $\operatorname{MC}(\mathbf{B})$ are pairs $(M,q)$, where $M$ is an object of $\mathbf{B}$, and $q\colon M\to M$ is a degree $1$ morphism such that $dq+q^{2}=0$. • A degree $p$ morphism $f\colon(M,q)\to(M^{\prime},q^{\prime})$ is a degree $p$ morphism $M\to M^{\prime}$ in $\mathbf{B}$. The differential of $f$ is defined by: $d_{\operatorname{MC}(\mathbf{B})}(f)=d_{\mathbf{B}}f+q^{\prime}f-(-1)^{p}fq.$
Definition 3.2. Let $(M_{n+1}\xrightarrow{p_{n+1,n}}M_{n})_{n\geq 0}$ be a sequence of closed degree $0$ maps in $\mathsf{C}_{\mathrm{dg}}(\mathbf{A})$. Its (strictly dg-functorial) homotopy limit is defined as the shifted mapping cone $\mathrm{ho}\!\varprojlim_{n}M_{i}=\operatorname{C}(1-\nu)[-1]$, sitting in the following pretriangle: $\mathrm{ho}\!\varprojlim_{n}M_{n}\to\prod_{n}M_{n}\xrightarrow{1-\nu}\prod_{n}% M_{n},$ where $\nu$ is the (closed, degree $0$) map induced by $\prod_{n}M_{n}\xrightarrow{\operatorname{pr}_{n+1}}M_{n+1}\xrightarrow{p_{n+1,% n}}M_{n}.$ Dually, let $(N_{n}\xrightarrow{j_{n,n+1}}N_{n+1})_{n\geq 0}$ be a sequence in $\mathsf{C}_{\mathrm{dg}}(\mathbf{A})$. Its (strictly dg-functorial) homotopy colimit is defined as the mapping cone $\mathrm{ho}\!\varinjlim_{n}N_{n}=\operatorname{C}(1-\mu)$, sitting in the following pretriangle: $\bigoplus_{n}N_{n}\xrightarrow{1-\mu}\bigoplus_{n}N_{n}\to\mathrm{ho}\!% \varinjlim_{n}N_{n},$ where $\mu$ is the (closed, degree $0$) map induced by $N_{n}\xrightarrow{j_{n,n+1}}N_{n+1}\xrightarrow{\operatorname{incl}_{n+1}}% \bigoplus_{n}N_{n}.$
Definition 7.9. The category $\operatorname{\mathsf{Hqe}}^{\mathrm{t-}}$ is defined as follows: • The objects are dg-categories $\mathbf{A}$ endowed with non-degenerate right bounded t-structure with enough derived projectives. • The morphisms are the morphisms $F\colon\mathbf{A}\to\mathbf{B}$ in $\operatorname{\mathsf{Hqe}}$ (isomorphism classes of quasi-functors) such that they admit a t-exact right adjoint $G\colon\mathbf{B}\to\mathbf{A}$ . We also denote by $\operatorname{\mathsf{Hqe}}^{\mathrm{t-}}_{\oplus}$ the full subcategory of $\operatorname{\mathsf{Hqe}}^{\mathrm{t-}}$ of dg-categories $\mathbf{A}$ such that the t-structure is closed under countable coproducts.
Definition 5.7. Let $\mathbf{Q}$ be a dg-category. A dg-module $M\in\mathsf{C}_{\mathrm{dg}}(\mathbf{Q})$ is called homotopically finitely presented (in short, hfp) if $H^{i}(M)$ is a finitely presented $H^{0}(\mathbf{Q})$-module for all $i\in\mathbb{Z}$: $H^{i}(M)\in\mathsf{mod}(H^{0}(\mathbf{Q})),\quad\forall\,i\in\mathbb{Z}.$ We denote by $\mathrm{h\textrm{-}proj}(\mathbf{Q})^{\mathrm{hfp}}$ and $\mathsf{D}(\mathbf{Q})^{\mathrm{hfp}}$ the full subcategories of respectively $\mathrm{h\textrm{-}proj}(\mathbf{Q})$ and $\mathsf{D}(\mathbf{Q})$ whose objects are the homotopically finitely presented $\mathbf{Q}$-dg-modules: $\displaystyle\mathrm{h\textrm{-}proj}(\mathbf{Q})^{\mathrm{hfp}}$ $\displaystyle=\{M\in\mathrm{h\textrm{-}proj}(\mathbf{Q}):H^{i}(M)\in\mathsf{% mod}(H^{0}(\mathbf{Q}))\ \ \forall\,i\},$ $\displaystyle\mathsf{D}(\mathbf{Q})^{\mathrm{hfp}}$ $\displaystyle=\{M\in\mathsf{D}(\mathbf{Q}):H^{i}(M)\in\mathsf{mod}(H^{0}(% \mathbf{Q}))\ \ \forall\,i\}.$ We shall also set: $\displaystyle\mathrm{h\textrm{-}proj}^{-}(\mathbf{Q})^{\mathrm{hfp}}$ $\displaystyle=\{M\in\mathrm{h\textrm{-}proj}(\mathbf{Q})^{\mathrm{hfp}}:H^{i}(% M)=0\quad\forall\,i\gg 0\},$ $\displaystyle\mathsf{D}^{-}(\mathbf{Q})^{\mathrm{hfp}}$ $\displaystyle=\{M\in\mathsf{D}(\mathbf{Q})^{\mathrm{hfp}}:H^{i}(M)=0\quad% \forall\,i\gg 0\}.$
Definition 6.1 ([19, §5.1]). Let $\mathbf{T}$ be a triangulated category with t-structure, and as usual denote $H^{0}=\tau_{\leq 0}\tau_{\geq 0}\colon\mathbf{T}\to\mathbf{T}^{\heartsuit}.$ (1) Assume that for all projectives $P\in\operatorname{Proj}(\mathbf{T}^{\heartsuit})$ in the heart the cohomological functor $\mathbf{T}^{\heartsuit}(P,H^{0}(-))\colon\mathbf{T}\to\mathsf{Mod}(\mathbf{k})$ is corepresentable: $\mathbf{T}^{\heartsuit}(P,H^{0}(-))\cong\mathbf{T}(S(P),-).$ We say that $S(P)$ is the derived projective associated to $P$. In this case, we also say that $\mathbf{T}$ has derived projectives. If $\mathbf{A}$ is a pretriangulated dg-category such that $H^{0}(\mathbf{A})$ has a t-structure, we shall say that $\mathbf{A}$ has derived projectives if $H^{0}(\mathbf{A})$ has this property. (2) Dually, assume that for all injectives $I\in\operatorname{Inj}(\mathbf{T}^{\heartsuit})$ in the heart, the cohomological functor $\mathbf{T}^{\heartsuit}(H^{0}(-),I)\colon{\mathbf{T}}^{\mathrm{op}}\to\mathsf{% Mod}(\mathbf{k})$ is representable: $\mathbf{T}^{\heartsuit}(H^{0}(-),I)\cong\mathbf{T}(-,L(I)).$ We say that $L(I)\in\mathbf{T}$ is the derived injective associated to $I$. In this case, we also say that $\mathbf{T}$ has derived injectives. If $\mathbf{A}$ is a pretriangulated dg-category such that $H^{0}(\mathbf{A})$ has a t-structure, we shall say that $\mathbf{A}$ has derived injectives if $H^{0}(\mathbf{A})$ has this property.
Definition 5.1. A (right) $\mathbf{C}$-module $M\in\mathsf{Mod}(\mathbf{C})$ is finitely presented if there is an exact sequence $\bigoplus_{j=1}^{m}\mathbf{C}(-,C^{\prime}_{j})\to\bigoplus_{i=1}^{n}\mathbf{C% }(-,C_{i})\to M\to 0,$ for some objects $C_{1},\ldots,C_{n}$ and $C^{\prime}_{1},\ldots,C^{\prime}_{m}$ in $\mathbf{C}$. The full subcategory of finitely presented modules of $\mathsf{Mod}(\mathbf{C})$ is denoted by $\mathsf{mod}(\mathbf{C})$.
Definition 7.7. The category $\operatorname{\mathsf{Hqe}}^{\mathrm{DGProj}}$ is defined as follows: • The objects are the homotopically locally coherent dg-categories $\mathbf{Q}$ such that $H^{0}(\mathbf{Q})$ is Karoubian. • The morphisms are the morphisms $F:\mathbf{Q}\to\mathbf{Q}^{\prime}$ in $\operatorname{\mathsf{Hqe}}$ (isomorphism classes of quasi-functors) with the property that for any $Q^{\prime}\in\mathbf{Q}^{\prime}$, the restricted module along the functor $H^{0}(F)$: $H^{0}(\mathbf{Q}^{\prime})(F(-),Q^{\prime})=H^{0}(\mathbf{Q}^{\prime})(H^{0}(F% )(-),Q^{\prime})$ lies in $\mathsf{mod}(H^{0}(\mathbf{Q}))$. We also denote by $\operatorname{\mathsf{Hqe}}^{\mathrm{DGProj}}_{\oplus}$ the full subcategory of $\operatorname{\mathsf{Hqe}}^{\mathrm{DGProj}}$ of dg-categories $\mathbf{Q}$ such that $H^{0}(\mathbf{Q})$ is closed under countable coproducts.
Definition 5.4. Let $f\colon C\to C^{\prime}$ be a morphism in $\mathbf{C}$. A weak kernel of $f$ is a morphism $g\colon D\to C$ such that the sequence $\mathbf{C}(-,D)\xrightarrow{g_{*}}\mathbf{C}(-,C)\xrightarrow{f_{*}}\mathbf{C}% (-,C^{\prime})$ is exact in $\mathsf{Mod}(\mathbf{C})$. If every morphism in $\mathbf{C}$ has a weak kernel, we say that $\mathbf{C}$ admits weak kernels.
Definition 4.4. A (bounded above) one-sided twisted complex on $\mathbf{A}$ is a pair $(\oplus_{i\in\mathbb{Z}}A_{i}[-i],q)\in\operatorname{MC}(\mathbf{A}^{% \leftarrow})$, where $q=(q_{i}^{j}\colon A_{i}[-i]\to A_{j}[-j])_{i,j\in\mathbb{Z}}$ is such that $q_{i}^{j}=0$ whenever $j\leq i$. A one-sided morphism of degree $p$ $f\colon(\oplus_{i\in\mathbb{Z}}A_{i}[-i],q)\to(\oplus_{i\in\mathbb{Z}}B_{i}[-i% ],q^{\prime})$ between one-sided twisted complexes is a morphism $f=(f_{i}^{j}\colon A_{i}[-i]\to B_{j}[-j])_{i,j\in\mathbb{Z}}$ of degree $p$ in $\operatorname{MC}(\mathbf{A}^{\leftarrow})$ such that $f_{i}^{j}=0$ whenever $i-j+p>0$. The dg-subcategory of (bounded above) one-sided twisted complexes and one-sided morphisms in $\operatorname{MC}(\mathbf{A}^{\leftarrow})$ is denoted by $\operatorname{Tw}^{-}(\mathbf{A})$. The full dg-subcategory of $\operatorname{Tw}^{-}(\mathbf{A})$ whose objects are the bounded one-sided twisted complexes, namely the objects of the form $(\bigoplus_{i}A_{i}[-i],q)$ with $A_{i}=0$ for $i\gg 0$ or $i\ll 0$, is denoted by $\operatorname{Tw}^{-}_{\mathrm{b}}(\mathbf{A})$.
Definition 3.3. Let $(A_{n}\xrightarrow{j_{n,n+1}}A_{n+1})_{n\geq 0}$ be a sequence of closed degree $0$ maps in $\mathbf{A}$, and let $\mathrm{ho}\!\varprojlim_{n}\mathbf{A}(A_{n},-)$ be the strictly dg-functorial homotopy limit of the induced sequence $(\mathbf{A}(A_{n+1},-)\xrightarrow{j^{*}_{n,n+1}}\mathbf{A}(A_{n},-))_{n}$ in $\mathsf{C}_{\mathrm{dg}}(\mathbf{A})$. The (dg-functorial) homotopy colimit of $(A_{n}\to A_{n+1})_{n}$ is an object $\mathrm{ho}\!\varinjlim_{n}A_{n}$ together with an isomorphism $\mathbf{A}(\mathrm{ho}\!\varinjlim_{n}A_{n},-)\to\mathrm{ho}\!\varprojlim_{n}% \mathbf{A}(A_{n},-)$ in the derived category $\mathsf{D}({\mathbf{A}}^{\mathrm{op}})$.
Definition 3.8. We say that the t-structure $(\mathbf{T}_{\leq 0},\mathbf{T}_{\geq 0})$ is closed under countable coproducts if the aisle $\mathbf{T}_{\leq 0}$ is closed under countable coproducts. Dually, we say that the t-structure $(\mathbf{T}_{\leq 0},\mathbf{T}_{\geq 0})$ is closed under countable products if $\mathbf{T}_{\geq 0}$ is closed under countable products.
Definition 5.8. A dg-category $\mathbf{Q}$ is called (right) homotopically locally coherent (in short, hlc) if: • $\mathbf{Q}$ is cohomologically concentrated in nonpositive degrees: for all $A,A^{\prime}\in\mathbf{Q}$, we have $H^{i}(\mathbf{Q}(A,A^{\prime}))=0$ for all $i>0$. • $H^{0}(\mathbf{Q})$ is an additive and (right) coherent $\mathbf{k}$-linear category. • For all $A\in\mathbf{Q}$, the represented dg-module $\mathbf{Q}(-,A)$ is homotopically finitely presented, in other words the $H^{0}(\mathbf{Q})$-module $H^{i}(\mathbf{Q}(-,A))$ is finitely presented for all $i\in\mathbb{Z}$: $H^{i}(\mathbf{Q}(-,A))\in\mathsf{mod}(H^{0}(\mathbf{Q}))$.
Definition 6.5. Let $\mathbf{T}$ be a triangulated category with t-structure. We say that $\mathbf{T}$ has enough derived projectives if $\mathbf{T}$ has derived projectives as in Definition 6.1 and moreover the heart $\mathbf{T}^{\heartsuit}$ has enough projectives. Dually, we say that $\mathbf{T}$ has enough derived injectives if $\mathbf{T}$ has derived injectives and $\mathbf{T}^{\heartsuit}$ has enough injectives. If $\mathbf{A}$ is a pretriangulated dg-category with a t-structure, we say that $\mathbf{A}$ has enough derived projectives (or injectives) if $H^{0}(\mathbf{A})$ has this property.
Definition 3.1. Let $(A_{n}\xrightarrow{j_{n,n+1}}A_{n+1})_{n\geq 0}$ be a sequence of maps in $\mathbf{T}$. The homotopy colimit $\mathrm{ho}\!\varinjlim_{n}A_{n}$ is defined as the object (uniquely determined up to isomorphism) sitting in the following distinguished triangle: $\bigoplus_{n}A_{n}\xrightarrow{1-\mu}\bigoplus_{n}A_{n}\to\mathrm{ho}\!% \varinjlim_{n}A_{n},$ where $\mu$ is the map induced by $A_{n}\xrightarrow{j_{n,n+1}}A_{n+1}\xrightarrow{\operatorname{incl}_{n+1}}% \bigoplus_{n}A_{n}.$ A homotopy limit is defined as a homotopy colimit in ${\mathbf{T}}^{\mathrm{op}}$. Explicity, assume that every direct product we shall write exists in $\mathbf{T}$, and let $(A_{n+1}\xrightarrow{\pi_{n+1,n}}A_{n})_{n\geq 0}$ be a sequence of maps in $\mathbf{T}$. Then, the homotopy limit $\mathrm{ho}\!\varprojlim_{n}A_{n}$ is defined as the object (uniquely determined up to isomorphism) sitting in the following distinguished triangle: $\mathrm{ho}\!\varprojlim_{n}A_{n}\to\prod_{n}A_{n}\xrightarrow{1-\nu}\prod_{n}% A_{n},$ where $\nu$ is the map induced by $\prod_{n}A_{n}\xrightarrow{\operatorname{pr}_{n+1}}A_{n+1}\xrightarrow{\pi_{n+% 1,n}}A_{n}.$
Definition 3.2. We call a protomodular algebra right-cancellable if it satisfies the equivalent conditions of Lemma 3.1.
Definition 2. An empirical model on a measurement scenario $\left\langle X,\mathcal{M},{\bm{O}}\right\rangle$ is a compatible family for the presheaf $\mathbb{P}\circ\mathcal{E}$ on the cover $\mathcal{M}$. Concretely, it is a family $e=\{e_{C}\}_{C\in\mathcal{M}}$, where $e_{C}$ is a probability measure on the space $\mathcal{E}(C)={\bm{O}}_{C}$ for each maximal context $C\in\mathcal{M}$, which satisfies the compatibility condition: $e_{C}|_{C\cap C^{\prime}}=e_{C^{\prime}}|_{C\cap C^{\prime}}\text{ .}$
Definition 7. A hidden-variable model $\left\langle\bm{\Lambda},p,k\right\rangle$ is deterministic if $k_{C}(\lambda,\text{--})\colon\mathcal{F}_{C}\longrightarrow[0,1]$ is a Dirac measure for every $\lambda\in\Lambda$ and for every maximal context $C\in\mathcal{M}$; in other words, there is an assignment $\mathbf{o}\in O_{C}$ such that $k_{C}(\lambda,\text{--})=\delta_{\mathbf{o}}$.
Definition 11. Let $e$ be an empirical model on the scenario $\left\langle X,\mathcal{M},{\bm{O}}\right\rangle$. The noncontextual fraction of $e$, written $\textsf{NCF}(e)$, is defined as $\sup\left\{\mu(O_{X})\mid\mu\in\mathbb{M}({\bm{O}}_{X}),\,\forall{C\in\mathcal% {M}}\bm{.}\;\mu|_{C}\leq e_{C}\right\}\text{ .}$ Note that since $e_{C}\in\mathbb{P}({\bm{O}}_{C})$ for all $C\in\mathcal{M}$ it follows that $\textsf{NCF}(e)\in[0,1]$. The contextual fraction of $e$, written $\textsf{CF}(e)$, is given by $\textsf{CF}(e)\mathrel{\mathchoice{\vbox{\hbox{$\displaystyle:$}}}{\vbox{\hbox% {$\textstyle:$}}}{\vbox{\hbox{$\scriptstyle:$}}}{\vbox{\hbox{$% \scriptscriptstyle:$}}}{=}}1-\textsf{NCF}(e)$.
Definition 4. Let $\left\langle X,\mathcal{M},{\bm{O}}\right\rangle$ be a measurement scenario. A hidden-variable model8The alternative term ontological model [73] has become widely used in quantum foundations in recent years. It indicates that the hidden variable, sometimes referred to as the ontic state, is supposed to provide an underlying description of the physical world at perhaps a more fundamental level than the empirical-level description, via the quantum state for example. on this scenario consists of the following ingredients: • A measurable space $\bm{\Lambda}=\left\langle\Lambda,\mathcal{F}_{\Lambda}\right\rangle$ of hidden variables. • A probability measure $p$ on $\bm{\Lambda}$. • For each maximal context $C\in\mathcal{M}$, a probability kernel $k_{C}\colon\bm{\Lambda}\longrightarrow\mathcal{E}(C)$, satisfying the following compatibility condition:9Recall from Section 2 that a probability kernel $k_{C}\colon\bm{\Lambda}\longrightarrow\mathcal{E}(C)$ is a function $k_{C}\colon\Lambda\times\mathcal{F}_{C}\longrightarrow[0,1]$ which is a measurable function in the first argument and a probability measure in the second argument. $\forall{\lambda\in\Lambda}\bm{.}\;\quad k_{C}(\lambda,-)|_{C\cap C^{\prime}}=k% _{C^{\prime}}(\lambda,-)|_{C\cap C^{\prime}}\text{ .}$
Definition 8. A hidden-variable model $\left\langle\bm{\Lambda},p,k\right\rangle$ is factorisable if $k_{C}(\lambda,\text{--})\colon\mathcal{F}_{C}\longrightarrow[0,1]$ factorises as a product measure for every $\lambda\in\Lambda$ and for every maximal context $C\in\mathcal{M}$. That is, for any family of measurable sets $\mathopen{(}B_{x}\in\mathcal{F}_{x}\mathclose{)}_{x\in C}$, $k_{C}(\lambda,\prod_{x\in C}B_{x})=\prod_{x\in C}k_{C}|_{\mathopen{\{}x% \mathclose{\}}}(\lambda,B_{x})$ where $k_{C}|_{\mathopen{\{}x\mathclose{\}}}(\lambda,\text{--})$ is the marginal of the probability measure $k_{C}(\lambda,\text{--})$ on ${\bm{O}}_{C}=\prod_{x\in C}{\bm{O}}_{x}$ to the space ${\bm{O}}_{\mathopen{\{}x\mathclose{\}}}={\bm{O}}_{x}$.10 Note that, due to the assumption of parameter independence (Eq. (4)), we can unambiguously write $k_{x}(\lambda,\text{--})$ for $k_{C}|_{\mathopen{\{}x\mathclose{\}}}$, as this marginal is independent of the context $C$ from which one is restricting.
Definition 13. A generalised Bell inequality $(\mathbf{\beta},R)$ on a measurement scenario $\left\langle X,\mathcal{M},{\bm{O}}\right\rangle$ is a family $\mathbf{\beta}=(\beta_{C})_{C\in\mathcal{M}}$ with $\beta_{C}\in C_{0}(O_{C},\mathbb{R})$ for all $C\in\mathcal{M}$, together with a bound $R\in\mathbb{R}$, such that for all noncontextual empirical models $e$ on $\left\langle X,\mathcal{M},{\bm{O}}\right\rangle$ it holds that $\langle\beta,e\rangle_{2}\mathrel{\mathchoice{\vbox{\hbox{$\displaystyle:$}}}{% \vbox{\hbox{$\textstyle:$}}}{\vbox{\hbox{$\scriptstyle:$}}}{\vbox{\hbox{$% \scriptscriptstyle:$}}}{=}}\sum_{C\in\mathcal{M}}\int_{O_{C}}\beta_{C}\;\,% \mathrm{d}\,e_{C}\leq R$. The normalised violation of a generalised Bell inequality $(\mathbf{\beta},R)$ by an empirical model $e$ is $\max\{0,\langle\beta,e\rangle_{2}\}/(\|\beta\|-R)$ where $\|\beta\|\mathrel{\mathchoice{\vbox{\hbox{$\displaystyle:$}}}{\vbox{\hbox{$% \textstyle:$}}}{\vbox{\hbox{$\scriptstyle:$}}}{\vbox{\hbox{$\scriptscriptstyle% :$}}}{=}}\sum_{C\in\mathcal{M}}\|\beta_{C}\|=\sum_{C\in\mathcal{M}}\sup\left\{% f(\mathbf{o})\mid\mathbf{o}\in O_{C}\right\}$.14The notation $\langle\cdot,\cdot\rangle_{2}$ is further discussed and explained to be a canonical duality in Appendix A.
Definition 6. Let $\left\langle X,\mathcal{M},{\bm{O}}\right\rangle$ be a measurement scenario and $\left\langle\bm{\Lambda},p,k\right\rangle$ be a hidden-variable model. Then the corresponding empirical model $e$ is given by $e_{C}(B)=\int_{\Lambda}k_{C}(\text{--},B)\;\,\mathrm{d}\,p=\int_{\lambda\in% \Lambda}k_{C}(\lambda,B)\;\,\mathrm{d}\,p(\lambda)\text{ .}$
Definition 1. A measurement scenario is a triple $\left\langle X,\mathcal{M},{\bm{O}}\right\rangle$ whose elements are specified as follows. • $X$ is a finite set of measurement labels. • $\mathcal{M}$ is a covering family of subsets of $X$, i.e. such that $\bigcup\mathcal{M}=X$. The elements $C\in\mathcal{M}$ are called maximal contexts and represent maximal sets of compatible observables. We therefore require that $\mathcal{M}$ be an anti-chain with respect to subset inclusion, i.e. that no element of this family is a proper subset of another. Any subset of a maximal context also represents a set of compatible measurements, and we refer to elements of ${\mathcal{U}\mathrel{\mathchoice{\vbox{\hbox{$\displaystyle:$}}}{\vbox{\hbox{$% \textstyle:$}}}{\vbox{\hbox{$\scriptstyle:$}}}{\vbox{\hbox{$\scriptscriptstyle% :$}}}{=}}\left\{U\subseteq C\mid C\in\mathcal{M}\right\}}$ as contexts.5While it is more convenient to specify $\mathcal{M}$, note that the set of contexts $\mathcal{U}$ carries exactly the same information. It forms an abstract simplicial complex whose simplices are the contexts and whose facets are the maximal context. This combinatorial topological structure is emphasised in some presentations [16, 17, 30, 48, 5]. • ${\bm{O}}=\mathopen{(}{\bm{O}}_{x}\mathclose{)}_{x\in X}$ specifies a measurable space of outcomes ${\bm{O}}_{x}=\left\langle O_{x},\mathcal{F}_{x}\right\rangle$ for each measurement $x\in X$.
Definition 3. An empirical model $e$ on a scenario $\left\langle X,\mathcal{M},{\bm{O}}\right\rangle$ is extendable (or noncontextual) if there is a probability measure $\mu$ on the space $\mathcal{E}(X)={\bm{O}}_{X}$ such that $\mu|_{C}=e_{C}$ for every $C\in\mathcal{M}$.7Notions of partial extendability have also been considered in the discrete setting in [57, 71].
Definition 1.1. Let $\mathbb{G}$ be the category obtained as the quotient of the free category on the graph $\tikzcd 0{}{}{}{}{}{}{}{}{}{}\xy@@ix@{{\hbox{}}}$
Definition 5.1 ([9]). A regular category $\mathbb{C}$ is said to be factor permutable if for any equivalence relation $E$ on any object $A$ in $\mathbb{C}$ we have $F\circ E=E\circ F$ for any factor relation $F\in F(A)$.
Definition 4.1. An object $X$ in a regular category $\mathbb{C}$ is said to have global support if any terminal morphism $X\rightarrow 1$ is a regular epimorphism.
Definition 7.1. An object $X$ in a category with finite products is said to have factorable congruences if for any effective equivalence relation $E$ on $X$, and any product diagram $A\xleftarrow{\pi_{1}}X\xrightarrow{\pi_{2}}B$, there exist effective equivalence relations $E_{1}$ and $E_{2}$ such that $E_{1}\times E_{2}=E$.
Definition 2.1. An object $X$ in a category $\mathbb{C}$ is called projection-coextensive if it is $\mathcal{M}$-coextensive with $\mathcal{M}$ the class of all product projections in $\mathbb{C}$.
Definition 4.3. A factor relation on an object $X$ is an equivalence relation $F$ represented by the kernel equivalence relation of a product projection $X\xrightarrow{p}A$ of $X$. A factor relation represented by the kernel equivalence relation of a complement of $p$ is correspondingly called a complement of $F$, and will often be denoted by $F^{\prime}$. The poset $F(X)$ of factor relations on $X$ is bounded with top element $\nabla_{X}$ and bottom element $\Delta_{X}$.
Definition 3.1. Let $X$ be an object in a category $\mathbb{C}$, then by $\mathrm{Proj}_{\mathbb{C}}(X)$ we mean the full subcategory of $X\downarrow\mathbb{C}$ consisting of product projections of $X$. If $X$ has epimorphic product projections, then $\mathrm{Proj}_{\mathbb{C}}(X)$ is a preorder, so that in particular, if $X$ is projection-coextensive then $\mathrm{Proj}_{\mathbb{C}}(X)$ is a preorder (see Proposition 2.1). In what follows we shall write $\mathrm{Proj}(X)$ for the posetal-reflection of $\mathrm{Proj}_{\mathbb{C}}(X)$ when $X$ has epimorphic product projections.
Definition 6.2 ([4]). Let $\mathbb{C}$ be a Mal’tsev category, and let $(r_{1},r_{2}):R_{0}\rightarrow X\times X$ and $(s_{1},s_{2}):S_{0}\rightarrow X\times X$ represent two equivalence relations $R$ and $S$ on an object $X$, respectively. Consider the pullback below: $\xymatrix{R_{0}\times_{X}S_{0}\ar[r]^{-}{p_{1}}\ar[d]_{-}{p_{2}}&S_{0}\ar[d]^{% s_{1}}\\ R_{0}\ar[r]_{r_{2}}&X}$ A connector between $R_{0}$ and $S_{0}$ is a morphism $p:R_{0}\times_{X}S_{0}\rightarrow X$ such that $xRp(x,y,z)Sz$ and $p(x,y,y)=x=p(y,y,x).$ If there exists a representative of $R$ which admits a connector with a representative of $S$, then we say that $R$ and $S$ are connected, or that the pair $(R,S)$ are commuting.
Definition 1.1. Let $\mathbb{C}$ be a category and $\mathcal{M}$ a class of morphisms from $\mathbb{C}$. A commutative square $\xymatrix{X\ar[r]\ar[d]&A\ar[d]^{a}\\ B\ar[r]_{b}&P}$ in $\mathbb{C}$ is called an $\mathcal{M}$-pushout if it is a pushout in $\mathbb{C}$, and $a,b$ are morphisms in $\mathcal{M}$.
Definition 4.2. In what follows we will write $\mathrm{Eq}(X)$ for poset of all equivalence relations on an object $X$, and $\mathrm{Ef}(X)$ for the poset of all effective equivalence relations on $X$.
Definition 6.1 ([6, 7]). A finitely complete category $\mathbb{C}$ is Mal’tsev if any reflexive relation is an equivalence relation.
Definition 2.2. An object $X$ in a category $\mathbb{C}$ is said to have the (finite) strict refinement property if for any two (finite) product diagrams $(X\xrightarrow{f_{i}}A_{i})_{i\in I}$ and $(X\xrightarrow{g_{j}}B_{j})_{j\in J}$, there exist families of morphisms $(A_{i}\xrightarrow{\alpha_{i,j}}C_{i,j})_{i\in I,j\in J}$ and $(B_{j}\xrightarrow{\beta_{i,j}}C_{i,j})_{i\in I,j\in J}$ such that $\alpha_{i,j}f_{i}=\beta_{i,j}g_{j}$ and the diagrams $(A_{i}\xrightarrow{\alpha_{i,s}}C_{i,s})_{s\in J}$ and $(B_{j}\xrightarrow{\beta_{t,j}}C_{t,j})_{t\in I}$ are product diagrams for any $i\in I$ and $j\in J$.
Definition 7.2. An object $X$ in a category $\mathbb{C}$ is said to be regularly-coextensive if it is $\mathcal{M}$-coextensive with $\mathcal{M}$ the class of all regular epimorphisms in $\mathbb{C}$.
Definition 4.4. A regular category $\mathbb{C}$ is said to be pre-exact if it admits coequalizers of equivalence relations, and for any two equivalence relations $E_{1}$ and $E_{2}$, we have $\overline{E_{1}\cap E_{2}}=\overline{E_{1}}\cap\overline{E_{2}}$.
Definition 1.2. Let $\mathbb{C}$ be a category and $\mathcal{M}$ a class of morphisms in $\mathbb{C}$. An object $X$ is said to be $\mathcal{M}$-coextensive if every morphism in $\mathcal{M}$ with domain $X$ admits an $\mathcal{M}$-pushout along every product projection of $X$, and in each commutative diagram $\xymatrix{A_{1}\ar[d]&X\ar[r]\ar[d]\ar[l]&A_{2}\ar[d]\\ B_{1}&\ar[r]Y\ar[l]&B_{2}}$ where the top row is a product diagram and the vertical morphisms belong to $\mathcal{M}$, the bottom row is a product diagram if and only if both squares are $\mathcal{M}$-pushouts.
Definition 6.3. An object $X$ in a regular Mal’tsev category $\mathbb{C}$ is said to be centerless if for any equivalence relation $E$ on $X$, we have that if $(E,\nabla_{X})$ are commuting then $E=\Delta_{X}$.
Definition 2.9. Given a query $(A,B,C)\in Q_{\Sigma}$, the canonical $\Sigma$-model $CM(\varphi)\in M_{\Sigma}(A+B)$ is defined by $CM(\varphi)(R)=\set{\vec{x}\in(A+B)^{\mathtt{ar}(R)}\ }{\ (R,\vec{x})\in C}$.
Definition 1.3. A pregroup is a pro-monoid $P$ where every type $t\in P$ has a pair of left and right adjoints ${}^{\star}t$ and $t^{\star}$ such that: • $t({}^{\star}t)\enspace\leq\enspace\epsilon\enspace\leq\enspace({}^{\star}t)t$ (left adjunction) • $(t^{\star})t\enspace\leq\enspace\epsilon\enspace\leq\enspace t(t^{\star})$ (right adjunction) We say that a pregroup is strict when for all $s,t\in P$ we have: • ${}^{\star}(t^{\star})\enspace=\enspace t\enspace=\enspace({}^{\star}t)^{\star}$ (cancellation) • ${}^{\star}(st)=({}^{\star}t)({}^{\star}s)\enspace\land\enspace(st)^{\star}=(t^% {\star})(s^{\star})$ (monoid anti-hom.) Given a graph $I\subseteq B^{2}$, let $P(B)=List(B\times\mathbb{Z})$ be the least pro-monoid induced by: • $(a,b)\in I\enspace\implies\enspace(a,0)\leq(b,0)$ (induced step) • $(b,z)(b,z-1)\enspace\leq\enspace\epsilon$ (contraction) • $\epsilon\enspace\leq\enspace(b,z)(b,z+1)$ (expansion) Note that we identify $(b,0)\in P(B)$ with $b\in B$, called a basic type.
Definition 3.9. Problem 3.10.
